        },
        {
            "decision": "If you have additional questions, or [**Male First Name (un) **]??????t understand something about your operation, please call your [**Male First Name (un) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12268,
            "end_offset": 12431,
            "annotation_id": "NU_118"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Do not drive until you have stopped taking pain medicine and feel you could respond in an emergency.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12443,
            "end_offset": 12542,
            "annotation_id": "NU_119"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may climb stairs",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12544,
            "end_offset": 12564,
            "annotation_id": "NU_120"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may go outside. But avoid traveling long distances until you see your [**Male First Name (un) 5059**] at your next visit.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12566,
            "end_offset": 12690,
            "annotation_id": "NU_121"
        },
        {
            "decision": "[**Male First Name (un) **]??????t lift more than 20-25 pounds for 6 weeks. (This is about the weight of a briefcase or a bag of groceries.) This applies to lifting children, but they may sit on your lap.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12692,
            "end_offset": 12895,
            "annotation_id": "NU_122"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may start some light exercise when you feel comfortable",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12897,
            "end_offset": 12956,
            "annotation_id": "NU_123"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You will need to stay out of bathtubs or swimming pools for a time while your incision is healing. Ask your doctor when you can resume tub baths or swimming.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 12958,
            "end_offset": 13114,
            "annotation_id": "NU_124"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Heavy exercise may be started after 6 weeks, but use common sense and go slowly at first.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 13116,
            "end_offset": 13204,
            "annotation_id": "NU_125"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may resume sexual activity unless your doctor has told you otherwise.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 13206,
            "end_offset": 13278,
            "annotation_id": "NU_126"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may feel weak or ??????washed out?????? for 6 weeks. You might want to nap often. Simple tasks may exhaust you. You may have a sore throat because of a tube that was in your throat during surgery. You might have trouble concentrating or difficulty sleeping. You might feel somewhat depressed. You could have a poor appetite for a while. Food may seem unappealing. All these feelings and reactions are normal and should go away in a short time. If they do not, tell your [**Month (only) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 13314,
            "end_offset": 13811,
            "annotation_id": "NU_127"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may gently wash away dried material around your incision",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 13914,
            "end_offset": 13974,
            "annotation_id": "NU_128"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Do not remove steri-strips for 2 weeks. (These are the thin paper strips that might be on your incision.) But if they fall off before that, it??????s OK.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 13976,
            "end_offset": 14128,
            "annotation_id": "NU_129"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Avoid direct sun exposure to the incision area",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 14203,
            "end_offset": 14249,
            "annotation_id": "NU_130"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Do not use any ointments on the incision unless you were told otherwise",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 14251,
            "end_offset": 14322,
            "annotation_id": "NU_131"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may see a small amount of clear or light red fluid staining your dressing or clothes. If the staining is severe, please call your [**Month (only) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 14324,
            "end_offset": 14481,
            "annotation_id": "NU_132"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You may shower. As noted above, ask your doctor when you may resume tub baths or swimming.",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 14483,
            "end_offset": 14572,
            "annotation_id": "NU_133"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Constipation is a common side effect of medicine ",
            "category": "Category 3: Defining problem",
            "start_offset": 14665,
            "end_offset": 14713,
            "annotation_id": "NU_134"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Percocet or codeine",
            "category": "Category 5: Drug related",
            "start_offset": 14722,
            "end_offset": 14741,
            "annotation_id": "NU_135"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If needed, you may take a stool softener (such as Colace, one capsule) or gentle laxative (such as Milk of Magnesia, 1 tablespoon) twice a day",
            "category": "Category 5: Drug related",
            "start_offset": 14743,
            "end_offset": 14885,
            "annotation_id": "NU_136"
        },
        {
            "decision": "After some operations, diarrhea can occur",
            "category": "Category 3: Defining problem",
            "start_offset": 15025,
            "end_offset": 15066,
            "annotation_id": "NU_137"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Drink plenty of fluids and see if it goes away. If it does not go away, or is severe and you feel ill, please call your [**Male First Name (un) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 15154,
            "end_offset": 15305,
            "annotation_id": "NU_138"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you find the pain is getting worse instead of better, please contact your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 15490,
            "end_offset": 15588,
            "annotation_id": "NU_139"
        },
        {
            "decision": "You will receive a prescription from your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**] for pain medicine to take by mouth. It is important you take this medicine as directed. Do not take it more frequently than prescribed. Do not take more medicine at one time than prescribed. Your pain medicine will work better if you take it before your pain gets too severe",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 15590,
            "end_offset": 15928,
            "annotation_id": "NU_140"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Talk with your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**] about how long you will need to take prescription pain medicine. Please [**Male First Name (un) **]??????t take any other pain medicine, including non-prescription pain medicine, unless your [**Male First Name (un) 5059**] has said it is OK",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 15930,
            "end_offset": 16207,
            "annotation_id": "NU_141"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you are experiencing no pain, it is OK to skip a dose of pain medicine. To reduce pain, remember to exhale with any exertion or when you change positions",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 16209,
            "end_offset": 16365,
            "annotation_id": "NU_142"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Remember to use your ??????cough pillow?????? for splinting when you cough or when you are doing your deep breathing exercises",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 16367,
            "end_offset": 16493,
            "annotation_id": "NU_143"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you experience any of the following, please contact your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**]: sharp pain or any severe pain that lasts several hours pain that is getting worse over time pain accompanied by fever of more than 101 a drastic change in nature or quality of your pain",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 16495,
            "end_offset": 16763,
            "annotation_id": "NU_144"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Take all the medicines you were on before the operation just as you did before, unless you have been told differently",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 16778,
            "end_offset": 16895,
            "annotation_id": "NU_145"
        },
        {
            "decision": "If you have any questions about what medicine to take or not to take, please call your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**].",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 16978,
            "end_offset": 17086,
            "annotation_id": "NU_146"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Please call your [**Name2 (NI) 5059**] or go to the emergency room if you develop: Worsening abdominal pain Sharp or severe pain that lasts several hours Temperature of 101 degrees or higher Severe diarrhea Vomiting Redness around the incision that is spreading Increased swelling around the incision Excessive bruising around the incision Cloudy fluid coming from the wound Bright red blood or foul smelling discharge coming from the wound An increase in drainage from the wound",
            "category": "Category 9: Advice and precaution",
            "start_offset": 17102,
            "end_offset": 17581,
            "annotation_id": "NU_147"
        },
        {
            "decision": "Call the Acute Care Clinic at [**Telephone/Fax (1) 600**] upon discharge to arrange a follow up appointment in [**3-3**] weeks. Office is located at [**Hospital1 18**], [**Hospital 2577**] Medical Office Building, [**Location (un) **].",
